# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-ohio-gubernatorial-election] The **1803 Ohio gubernatorial election** was held on January 11, 1803, in order to elect the first Governor of Ohio upon Ohio acquiring statehood on March 1, 1803.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican nominee and former Speaker of the Northwest Territory House of Representatives Edward Tiffin defeated Federalist candidates Benjamin I.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-ohio-gubernatorial-election] On election day, January 11, 1803, Democratic-Republican nominee Edward Tiffin won the election by a margin of 5,133 votes against his foremost opponent Federalist candidate Benjamin I.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Gilman, establishing Democratic-Republican control over the new office of Governor.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Tiffin was sworn in as the first Governor of the new state of Ohio on March 3, 1803.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The **1802–03 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 26, 1802 (in New York) and December 14, 1803 (in New Jersey).
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives, either before or after the first session of the 8th United States Congress convened on October 17, 1803.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] They occurred during President Thomas Jefferson's first term in office.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] With the addition of the new state of Ohio's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1800 United States census, the size of the House increased from 106 to 142 seats.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The greatest population growth revealed in the 1800 census was in territories that constituted the western regions of the country at the time, a tremendous boost for Democratic-Republican candidates.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Nearly all of the new seats created in the reapportionment went to Democratic-Republicans, closely aligned as they were with the agrarian interests of Western farmers.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] As a result, the Democratic-Republicans won the largest proportion of seats that either they or the competing Federalists had ever been able to secure in any earlier Congress, a supermajority greater than two-thirds of the total number.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] These elections were the first following reapportionment after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Thirty-five new seats were added in reapportionment, with three states having no change in apportionment, and thirteen states gaining between 1 and 7 seats.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] One further seat was added for the new state of Ohio, which is included in this table below.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] There were special elections in 1802 and 1803 during the 7th United States Congress and 8th United States Congress.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Elections are sorted here by date then district.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Georgia gained 2 seats in reapportionment after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] It elected its representatives October 4, 1802, at-large on a general ticket.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Kentucky gained 4 seats to 6 in reapportionment after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Maryland gained 1 seat in reapportionment after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Rather than increasing the number of districts, however, Maryland made the Maryland 5 a plural district with 2 seats.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Massachusetts increased 3 seats to 17 in reapportionment after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Massachusetts law at the time required a majority for election to an office, which requirement was not met in the 6th district, requiring two additional ballots.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] New Hampshire increased its apportionment from 4 seats to 5 after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] New Jersey increased its apportionment from 5 seats to 6 after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The Federalists did not run any official candidates in 1802, but a few Federalists did receive scattered votes.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] New York's apportionment increased from 10 seats to 17 seats after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The state was subsequently redistricted.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] 11 open seats were available due to the increase in apportionment and retirement of incumbents.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] North Carolina increased its apportionment from 10 to 12 seats after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Pennsylvania increased its apportionment from 13 to 18 seats after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The state was re-districted from 12 into 11 districts, four of which were plural districts.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] South Carolina increased its apportionment from 6 seats to 8 after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Tennessee increased its apportionment from 1 seat to 3 seats after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Vermont increased its apportionment from 2 seats to 4 after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Vermont law at the time required a majority of votes to win an office, which frequently necessitated additional ballots.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Virginia increased its apportionment from 19 to 22 seats after the 1800 census.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Virginia's congressional delegation remained the largest of any state, but would lose this distinction permanently after the census of 1810.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Elections were held over three days in April 1803.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] The **1802–03 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1802 and 1803, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 1.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] The Democratic-Republican Party maintained and greatly expanded their majority of seats to over two-thirds of the Senate.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Accounting for the 1802 special elections in New York, Rhode Island, and South Carolina.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Unless noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] In these special elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1803; ordered by election date.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1803; ordered by state.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] All of the elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] In this special election, the winner was seated in 1803 after March 4.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] In this regular election, the winner was seated on March 4, 1805; ordered by state.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Federalist incumbent James Hillhouse (originally elected in 1796) was re-elected.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Samuel Smith won election over John Eager Howard by a margin of 21.05%, or 16 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] There were two elections to the class 1 seat.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] The New Jersey legislature failed to elect by the March 4, 1803, beginning of the term.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] The governor appointed Democratic-Republican John Condit September 1, 1803, to continue the term.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Condit was then unanimously elected November 3, 1803, to finish the term.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Democratic-Republican John Armstrong Jr., who had held the class 3 seat since 1801, resigned February 5, 1802, and Democratic-Republican DeWitt Clinton was elected February 23, 1802, to finish the term.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Clinton, however, resigned November 4, 1803, and Armstrong was appointed December 8, 1803, to his old seat.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Federalist Gouverneur Morris lost re-election to the class 1 seat to Democratic-Republican Theodorus Bailey in 1803.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] New Democratic-Republican senators were elected April 1, 1803.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Official records indicate that John Smith and Thomas Worthington were elected, and that Smith received the "long" term, while Worthington received the "short" one.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] They do not indicate if there were other candidates, or what the vote totals were.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Federalist Senator Nathaniel Chipman lost re-election to Democratic-Republican Israel Smith.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Smith received 102 votes in the Vermont House of Representatives and 9 from the Governor and Council.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Spencer received 75 votes from the House and 4 from the Governor and Council.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] There were two elections to the same seat as the newly-re-elected senator died at the beginning of the next term.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Two-term Democratic-Republican Stevens Mason was re-elected in 1803.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Mason died May 10, 1803, having just begun the new term.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Democratic-Republican John Taylor was appointed but chose not to run to finish the term.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1803-united-states-senate-elections-in-ohio] Venable was elected December 7, 1803, as the unanimous choice of the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] A presidential election was held in Ohio on November 4, 1804, as part of the 1804 United States presidential election.The Democratic-Republican Party's ticket of incumbent president Thomas Jefferson and former New York governor George Clinton defeated the Federalist Party's ticket.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The Democratic-Republicans were eager to avoid a factional conflict following legislative elections in 1803, which saw a coalition of Federalists and dissident Democratic-Republicans win control of the Ohio House of Representatives.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The Federalists proposed dividing the state into three single-member districts in order to improve their chances of winning any of the state's electoral votes, but the legislators ultimately rejected this plan in favor of choosing all three electors on a general ticket.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The Democratic-Republican members of the Ohio General Assembly held a caucus at Chillicothe, Ohio, in February and nominated three electors pledged to Jefferson.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The Federalist Party nominated its ticket in a public meeting in Cincinnati; in an attempt to win support from the dissident Democratic-Republican faction, the meeting named a ticket that included both Federalists and Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Although a gathering of Federalist members of Congress had nominated Charles Cotesworth Pinckney for president in February, the Federalist electors remained formally unpledged.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] In contrast to the previous year, Ohio Democratic-Republicans displayed remarkable unity at the polls, and Jefferson carried the state by a nearly 7:1 margin.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Ohio chose three electors on a statewide general ticket.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] Nineteenth-century election laws required voters to elect the members of the Electoral College individually, rather than as a block.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] This sometimes resulted in small differences in the number of votes cast for electors pledged to the same presidential nominee, if some voters did not vote for all the electors nominated by a party.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election-in-ohio] The following table compares the votes for the leading Democratic-Republican and Federalist electors to give an approximate sense of the statewide popular vote.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1805-ohio-gubernatorial-election] The **1805 Ohio gubernatorial election** was held on October 8, 1805, to elect the governor of Ohio.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1805-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Democratic-Republican governor Edward Tiffin won re-election against fellow Democratic-Republican candidate Nathaniel Massie and Federalist nominee Benjamin I.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1805-ohio-gubernatorial-election] On election day, October 8, 1805, incumbent Democratic-Republican governor Edward Tiffin won re-election by a margin of 5,305 votes against his foremost opponent, fellow Democratic-Republican candidate Nathaniel Massie, thereby retaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of governor.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1805-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Tiffin was sworn in for his second term on December 2, 1805.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The **1806–07 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 29, 1806 (in New York) and August 4, 1807 (in Tennessee).
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 10th United States Congress convened on October 26, 1807.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] They occurred during Thomas Jefferson's second term.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Elections were held for all 142 seats, representing 17 states.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The Democratic-Republicans continued to build on their huge supermajority.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] They were actually able to take over two more seats than they had in the previous Congress, which they controlled by a margin of better than three to one.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Commitment to agrarian policy allowed the Democratic-Republicans to dominate rural districts, which represented the bulk of the nation.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] On the other hand, supporters of the Federalists, even in their traditional base of support in the urban centers of coastal New England, continued to lament the ineffectiveness of their party and its lack of electoral appeal.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] With a net change of 2 seats between the two parties, this was the smallest net change in US history in the House of Representatives until 2024.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] There were special elections in 1806 and 1807 during the 9th United States Congress and 10th United States Congress.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Connecticut elected its members on September 15, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Delaware elected its member October 7, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Georgia elected its members October 6, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Kentucky elected its members August 4, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Maryland elected its members October 6, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Massachusetts elected its members November 3, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] New Hampshire elected its members August 25, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] New Jersey elected its members October 14–15, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The Federalists ran a mixed ticket consisting of 2 Federalists (Aaron Ogden and John Beatty) and 4 Democratic-Republicans (William Helms, Ebenezer Elmer, George Maxwell, and Adam Boyd), one of whom (William Helms) was also on the Democratic-Republican ticket.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The Federalists capitalized on resentment over the replacement on the official Democratic-Republican ticket of Ebenezer Elmer, from South Jersey, with Thomas Newbold from Monmouth County and the retention of James Sloan.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] This ticket was formed too late to gain sufficient support, but the Federalists did do much better in state elections that year than they had in previous elections.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] New York elected representatives to the 10th Congress on April 29 – May 1, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] This was the second and last election in which Districts 2 and 3 were elected on a joint ticket.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] New York redistricted in the next election.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] North Carolina elected its members August 15, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Ohio elected its member October 14, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Both candidates were Democratic-Republicans, but from election articles published in The Scioto Gazette it was suggested that James Pritchard was the candidate of the Ohio Quids and that in a few counties, notably Columbiana and Jefferson, he was also supported by the Federalists.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Pennsylvania elected its members October 14, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Rhode Island elected its members August 26, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Rhode Island law required a majority of votes to win.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] In this election, only one candidate won a majority on the first ballot, and so a run-off election was required to choose the second seat.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] South Carolina elected its members October 13–14, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Tennessee elected its members August 3–4, 1807, after the Congress began but before the first session met.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Vermont elected its members September 2, 1806.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Virginia elected its members in April 1807, after the Congress began but before the first session met.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] As in the previous congress, there were three territories with non-voting delegates in the 10th Congress.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] In Indiana Territory, the legislature elected the delegate.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] The source used did not have information about Mississippi or Orleans Territory.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1806-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-ohio] Mississippi used popular election in 1808, while Orleans Territory elected its delegate by the legislature in 1808, suggesting Orleans probably used legislative election this year, too.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] The **1807 Ohio gubernatorial election** was held on October 13, 1807, in order to elect the Governor of Ohio.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republican candidate and former Chief Justice of the Ohio Supreme Court Return J.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Meigs Jr. initially won the election against fellow Democratic-Republican candidates Nathaniel Massie and Thomas Worthington.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] However, it was determined by the Ohio State Legislature that Meigs did not meet the residency requirements in order to take office as Governor of Ohio.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] The Ohio State Legislature thereby declared Massie the winner of the election, but he refused to accept the position of Governor.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Therefor incumbent Democratic-Republican Acting Governor Thomas Kirker remained Governor until the next election.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] On election day, October 13, 1807, Democratic-Republican candidate Return J.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Meigs Jr. won the election by a margin of 692 votes against his foremost opponent fellow Democratic-Republican candidate Nathaniel Massie, thereby retaining Democratic-Republican control over the office of Governor.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Meigs was however disqualified by the Ohio State Legislature to serve as Governor and Massie refused the position after the Legislature offered it to him.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1807-ohio-gubernatorial-election] Therefor incumbent Democratic-Republican Acting Governor Thomas Kirker was sworn in for this term on December 13, 1807.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election] The **1863 Ohio gubernatorial election** was held on October 13, 1863.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election] National Union nominee John Brough defeated Democratic nominee Clement Vallandigham with 60.61% of the vote.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election] The campaign was dominated by Vallandingham's May 5 arrest, conviction, and deportation for a speech critical of President Abraham Lincoln and the conduct of the American Civil War.
[src:1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election/1863-ohio-gubernatorial-election] He was nominated in absentia by the Democratic Party.
